{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17637249","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17637249"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:03+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T18:40:03+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17643"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17643","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17643"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10357"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75465"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10357","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10357"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17643"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60974"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4948"},{"type":"tags","id":"7742"},{"type":"tags","id":"7838"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24219"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24225"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75465","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/75465"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA researcher wants to study gaming addiction patterns among Australian university students. They have access to a complete list of 50,000 enrolled students with their unique student identification numbers.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes how to obtain a simple random sample of 1,000 students from this population?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Choose students from the most representative faculties","Ask for volunteers through university email","Select every 50th student from the alphabetical list","Assign random numbers to all students and select the first 1,000 in numerical order","Select students present on campus during a specific day"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe correct approach is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eassign random numbers to all students and select the first 1,000 in numerical order\u003C/strong\u003E. This method ensures every student has an equal probability of selection, which is the defining characteristic of simple random sampling.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect approaches can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelecting every 50th student from the alphabetical list\u003C/strong\u003E - This is systematic sampling, which can introduce bias if there are underlying patterns in the alphabetical order\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChoosing students from the most representative faculties\u003C/strong\u003E - This is stratified sampling, which deliberately selects from subgroups rather than giving equal probability to all individuals\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAsking for volunteers through university email\u003C/strong\u003E - This introduces volunteer bias and self-selection bias\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESelecting students present on campus during a specific day\u003C/strong\u003E - This introduces convenience sampling bias and excludes students who are not physically present\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ESimple random sampling is particularly important in this context as it helps ensure the sample is representative of the whole student population, minimising selection bias that could affect the assessment of gaming addiction patterns.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Simple random sampling ensures every member of a population has an equal probability of being selected.","Random number generators or systematic selection after randomisation are valid methods for simple random sampling.","Simple random sampling helps minimise selection bias in research studies."],"references":["Sullivan LM. Essentials of biostatistics in public health. 3rd ed. Burlington (MA): Jones \u0026 Bartlett Learning; 2018.","Dawson B, Trapp RG. Basic \u0026 clinical biostatistics. 4th ed. New York: McGraw-Hill; 2004."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60974"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17643"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"60974","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/60974"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-29T20:44:15+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-30T00:55:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10357"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75465"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"76","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/76"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level II","synonyms":null,"description":"Understand (interpreting and summarizing information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"gr